Subject: Transition to AWS    [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0Hz3Yl:ref ]

TextBody:
Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer
Endpoint Protector by CoSoSys, now part of Netwrix
DLP | Device Control | Content Aware Protection | eDiscovery | Enforced Encryption
 www.endpointprotector.com

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,

2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer

On Thu, Nov 7, 2024 at 11:43?AM Netwrix Support <techsupport@netwrix.com> wrote:


Hi Kristen,

Please let us know your current server version, and if the AWS server will be on the same network as the Azure one, and if you want the current logs to be moved to the new server.

The steps for the migration are the following:

1. You need to send us the Account ID for AWS + the Region
2. We will create a request for our DevOps to share the AWS image with you
3. You have to install the VM using the received image
4. We will perform a System Backup V2
5. Checking that both servers are the same regarding settings, computers, licenses, policies, etc.
6. You have to update the epp clients with the new IP

Note: While the clients are still communicating with the Azure server, the logs will be sent there, so some logs will be missing until the communication with AWS is finished. As an alternative, you can shut down the Azure server until all clients have the new server IP address set.


Best Regards,
Iosif Muntean| Technical Support Engineer
